  "text": "For decades, researchers have used green fluorescent proteins, also known as GFPs, to study how molecules move in living organisms, because GFPs can be tracked with a fluorescence microscope. GFPs diffuse rapidly: for example, one GFP molecule can travel the entire length of an E. coli cell in less than one second [CITATION_1] . However, adding a small positively-charged 'tag' to the negatively charged GFP slows its diffusion in E. coli [CITATION_2] .",
